130
00:09:19,209 --> 00:09:22,151
on the effects team was being given the opportunity

131
00:09:22,151 --> 00:09:27,214
to observe and then apply some of the principles

132
00:09:27,214 --> 00:09:29,995
of animation to our effects, namely timing,

133
00:09:29,995 --> 00:09:33,637
anticipation, exaggeration, and secondary action,

134
00:09:33,637 --> 00:09:38,020
which in turn aided us in having our effects

135
00:09:38,020 --> 00:09:39,241
mimic the character animations.

136
00:09:39,241 --> 00:09:44,964
So each animation asset was drawn frame by frame,

137
00:09:44,964 --> 00:09:45,264
meaning.

138
00:09:45,620 --> 00:09:48,261
no frames were skipped.

139
00:09:48,261 --> 00:09:50,782
If a flipbook needed 36 frames,

140
00:09:50,782 --> 00:09:53,863
then 36 frames of animation were drawn.

141
00:09:53,863 --> 00:09:55,804
So nothing was animated and then shortened

142
00:09:55,804 --> 00:09:59,025
or frames cut to fit a certain frame length.

143
00:09:59,025 --> 00:10:02,467
So because of that, we were able to break down

144
00:10:02,467 --> 00:10:04,847
whatever animation asset we were using,

145
00:10:04,847 --> 00:10:07,889
examine the frames, and integrate that technique

146
00:10:07,889 --> 00:10:09,589
used into whatever particle effect

147
00:10:09,589 --> 00:10:10,810
that we were creating at the time.

